rptwservicerwatchlistirp.commentActionToBeTaken: Loan is secured by a 19.6K sq ft retail property, located in Brooklyn, NY. The property was built in 1930, with renovations in 2016. There are two tenants: Apple (13.7K sq ft, 69.8% GLA) and The Corcoran Group (5.9K sq ft, 30.2% GLA). At UW, the loan had a DSCR of 1.33x with 96.4% occupancy. Loan is IO for full term. 11/02/2017: - YE 2016 DSCR is (0.02)x, with 100% occupancy. As of YTD June 2017, the DSCR has improved to 0.42x, with flat occupancy. Improvement is due to full revenues collected from The Corcoran group for Q1. In addition, Apple began rental payments in late May, 2017. This initial low performance was contemplated at UW. At the time of underwriting, Apple was in possession of its space and building out the two floors of the building. The Corcoran group only began paying rent in August, 2016, with a lease expiration in March, 2026. Performance is expected to continue to improve in 2017 with additional rental income.

The loan is secured by 4 self storage properties located in various cities in Michigan. In total, they contain 113.2K sq ft of storage space. The properties were built in 1960. At UW, the loan had a DSCR of 1.28x with a 93.7% occupancy (reported at the sum level). 09/06/2017: - The loan is on the watchlist due to major deferred maintenance reported on most recent inspection for the storage property located in Lansing, MI. The annual property inspection was conducted on 04/12/2017 and found the property to be in average condition for its age and market. Several deferred maintenance issues were noted including the following life safety concern: - Outdated fire extinguisher tags noted throughout the subject property. In addition to letters sent to borrower requesting borrower's remediation plan, servicer has contacted the borrower on numerous occasions. The borrower has not yet responded to calls or e-mails. Servicer will monitor accordingly.

rptwservicerwatchlistirp.commentActionToBeTaken: Loan is secured by a 142 unit multifamily property located in Oklahoma City, OK. The property was built in 1966, with renovations in 2014. At UW, the loan had a DSCR of 1.94x, with an occupancy of 90.1%. 11/02/2017: - YE 2016 DSCR was 1.35x with an occupancy of 79.6%. As of YTD June, 2017, the DSCR has fallen slightly to 1.25x. Per the borrower, the decline in performance from UW is due to a major pest control problem that they had early in 2016. This caused a number of move-outs as well as bad "word of mouth." They believe that the market is good and they should be at app. 90% occupancy. They are working diligently, with additional marketing plans and aggressive move-in offers. They are replacing the front area with new sod and flower gardens to improve curb appeal. They hope that this will increase traffic. Typically their high leasing period is over the summer, so they are hoping to be up to 90% by August. In addition, in April, 2017, the property suffered a fire, started by a lightning strike. The total amount of the replacement is $775,212.17. The borrower is working closely with both their insurance company and Servicers insurance department to ensure timely repairs. Per the most recent inspection, completed on 09/13/2017, the property has been found in average condition for its age and market. The inspector noted that the renovation is underway for the buildings that were affected by a fire from a lightning strike in April. Workers were onsite.

Loan is secured by a 60 unit multifamily property located in Hope Mills, NC. The property was built in 1983. At UW, the loan had a DSCR of 1.47x with an occupancy of 93.3%. 10/09/2017: - YE 2016 DSCR is 1.18x. As of YTD June 2017, the DSCR has fallen to 0.24x. Occupancy however, has improved from 48.3% to 51.7%. Currently, the occupancy is 63.3% and trending at 70%. The decline is due to higher vacancy costs, from units down for repairs. The property was affected by Hurricane Matthew on October 8/9th, 2016. Per the borrower, 24 units were down, however, only 8 were impacted. The local government required the entire building be shut down until repairs to the 8 damaged units were completed. Per the property management company, as of March 1st, all repairs have been materially completed. Servicer received a check from the insurance company and set up a loss draft reserve in the amount of $300K. At this time, no funds remain in the reserve; all have been disbursed to the borrower. They are currently running specials for the older section at a slightly lower than market while the newer section (rehabd) is running a little over.
